"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"278799",
"children":[
"Coma is a state of unarousable unresponsiveness. It may be caused by diffuse insults to the cerebral hemispheres, damage to the reticular activating system, or a combination of hemispheric and brainstem dysfunction. Unilateral hemispheric lesions do not result in coma unless edema and mass effect cause compression of the contralateral hemisphere or the reticular activating system. Coma may be caused by a variety of structural lesions and toxic, metabolic, and infectious causes."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"10cc73",
"children":[
"Patients in a vegetative state are unaware of self and the environment and show no purposeful responses to stimuli. They continue to have sleep-wake cycles and brainstem function."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"524d74",
"children":[
"The three cardinal findings of brain death are coma, absence of brainstem reflexes, and apnea."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_nr_s21_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"62546f",
"children":[
"Focal findings or any unexplained coma is an indication for emergent imaging of the brain to exclude hemorrhage or mass lesion. CT is the appropriate test in emergency situations. ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"lumbar puncture",
"children":[
"LP"
]
},
" is indicated when meningitis or ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"subarachnoid hemorrhage",
"children":[
"SAH"
]
},
" is suspected but neuroimaging is normal. Emergent ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"electroencephalogram",
"children":[
"EEG"
]
},
" can exclude nonconvulsive status epilepticus."
]
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"e39171",
"children":[
"Respiratory drive and motor posturing signs are incompatible with a diagnosis of brain death."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_nr_s21_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"ff8b18",
"children":[
"Attend to airway, breathing, and circulation first. All patients with unexplained coma should be urgently treated with thiamine and glucose (unless rapid finger-stick test rules out hypoglycemia). Give naloxone if an opioid overdose is suspected."
]
}
]
}
]
},
